liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Al-Awda Hospital in northern Gaza will likely have to close its doors in the next four or five days as it runs out of fuel, according to medical director Ahmed Muhanna. Dr Muhanna says he has been able to send five critical patients to a specialist centre but still has 10 in the hospital and is struggling to move them. "All the hospitals are overcrowded," he's told ABC News. "Even if I want to coordinate with other hospitals, I can't. They have no beds. They're putting patients in the corridors. "We have supplies for one-and-a-half months, but that's on regular days. In war days, the consumption increases more than 50 to 70 per cent. "This storage of medications will last 10-14 days maximum. Local markets cannot deliver anything for us and we can't get anything from outside. "We have enough fuel for four or five days maximum. The hospital will stop activities, we will close the doors." The World Health Organization says four hospitals in northern Gaza are no longer functioning as a result of damage and targeting and 21 hospitals in the Gaza Strip have received instructions from Israeli forces to evacuate. "Forced evacuation of hospitals may amount to a violation of International Humanitarian Law."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Northern Gaza hospital has just four or five days of power left

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: More Australians have left Israel overnight with three Australian government-organised flights enroute to Dubai. Australia's Foreign Minister Penny Wong said officials were looking to arrange another flight today, subject to security and operational constraints. Speaking to ABC News Breakfast, Senator Wong warned it could be the last repatriation flight for the foreseeable future and Australians in Lebanon should also consider leaving. "Look, this connects to the broader risk that so many countries of the world are seeking to avoid — and that is regional spillover," she said. "Obviously we see the events, tragic events in Israel, we see the humanitarian crisis in Gaza, but the thing that many countries are seeking to avert is regional spillover. In relation to Lebanon, what I've said to people is — please consider if you need to stay. We have not said, "Do not travel". But we have said "If you are there, please consider if your presence is essential". A lot of work was being done to by the United States, Egypt, Jordan — regional partners — to stop that spillover happening. Senator Wong also said despite work to get 19 Australians out of Gaza, efforts had so far not been successful.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australians in Lebanon should consider leaving says Foreign Minister Penny Wong

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: RedBridge Group Australia pollster and former Labor campaign strategist Kos Samaras spoke to ABC Radio National this morning, giving his perspective on the failures of the Yes campaign. He said the Yes campaign had failed to engage and educate outer suburban and regional communities about what the Voice proposal was about. "What we saw on the night was effectively what the polls were saying for weeks and months," Mr Samaras said. "The oldest, poorest areas … voted No in very significant numbers. "The Yes campaign failed to reach out to those outer suburban and regional communities and educate them about what this proposition was about, "A lot of booths were not staffed and that's a sign that most of the effort … was committed to where most of the social capital and interest in this referendum actually exist. "Teal seats voted significantly in favour of the Yes proposition." Mr Samaras provides more analysis on the failures of the Yes campaign in the story below:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Pollster says Yes campaign failed to reach out to outer suburban and regional voters

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: This morning ABC News' Casey Briggs looked into the referendum results in an attempt to answer whether Indigenous Australians were in support of a Voice. While he acknowledged that First Nations people would never have a uniform view on the referendum and it was ridiculous to expect everyone in any community to agree, the results from polling booths in remote communities reveal many wanted the Voice. "There are no electorates with a majority Indigenous population, but when you look at polling place results, the pattern is unmistakable," Briggs wrote. In the article below you can see a breakdown of the vote from electorates such as Lingiari and Lechhardt, where the Yes vote was as high as 73 per cent in remote communities:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: What percentage of Indigenous Australians voted in favour of the Voice?
